Due to the variability of the solar wind and the body’s rotation, we expect the magnetospheric topology to significantly change over time. While large planetary magnetospheres have extended regions with a quasi-fixed topology, a small magnetosphere of a quickly rotating body would continuously change its configuration as it reconnects to the external fields. Because of the periodicity of the rotation and the fact that similar wind condition would repeat during the mission, we will collect data from various times and bin them as a function of spacecraft locations in the PBF and PSO frames. This should enable us to construct several separate mean configurations for further study. For orbits that pass into and out of the magnetosphere, we will use the binned data to map the magnetopause surface. Magnetopause crossings can be identified from observing abrupt changes in the angle of B→der\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
